abstract: Michael Avenatti shot to fame from obscurity two years ago by taking to the airwaves as an outspoken, self-described nemesis of Donald Trump while representing adult film actress Stormy Daniels in lawsuits against the U.S. president.
snippet: Michael Avenatti shot to fame from obscurity two years ago by taking to the airwaves as an outspoken, self-described nemesis of Donald Trump while representing adult film actress Stormy Daniels in lawsuits against the U.S. president.
lead_paragraph: NEW YORK — Michael Avenatti shot to fame from obscurity two years ago by taking to the airwaves as an outspoken, self-described nemesis of Donald Trump while representing adult film actress Stormy Daniels in lawsuits against the U.S. president.
headline_main: Michael Avenatti Faces the Trial of His Life: His Own
headline_print_headline: Michael Avenatti Faces the Trial of His Life: His Own

abstract: The former vice president has made inaccurate claims this month about his record on Social Security, race and foreign policy.
snippet: The former vice president has made inaccurate claims this month about his record on Social Security, race and foreign policy.
lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. remains atop most national polls before the first votes are cast next month in the Democratic presidential primary. Before the Iowa caucuses, The New York Times reviewed recent statements he made defending his decades-long career, stressing his standing in the black community and highlighting his perceived strength on foreign policy. Here’s a fact check.

abstract: The cases against Julian Assange and Glenn Greenwald may be models for a crackdown.
snippet: The cases against Julian Assange and Glenn Greenwald may be models for a crackdown.
lead_paragraph: When Julian Assange, the WikiLeaks founder, was charged last year by the Trump administration in connection with the publication of secret United States government documents nearly a decade earlier, many journalists expressed deep concern about the dangerous precedent the case could set for investigative reporting in America.

abstract: It’s been more than three years since Russia's sweeping and systematic  effort to interfere in U.S. elections through disinformation on social media, stolen campaign emails and attacks on voting systems. U.S. officials have made advances in trying to prevent similar attacks from undermining the 2020 vote, but the potential threats have increased and some old problems have not been addressed. A look at what has changed since 2016 and what has not.
